  "notes": [
    {
      "id": "note_8",
      "text": "WORKFLOW: linear regression + residual diagnostics. Predict a continuous Y from X, then check the model is trustworthy — the second half is the part people skip. Step 1 — Fit Trend Curves (linear) reports the slope, intercept and R² (fraction of variance explained) and overlays the fitted line on the data. Step 2 — the DIAGNOSTIC: the residuals (observed − fitted) are plotted against X. A good fit leaves them scattered structurelessly around zero; a funnel shape means non-constant variance (heteroscedasticity), and a curve means the straight-line model is wrong — BOTH can hide behind a high R². Step 3 — a normality test on the residuals checks the assumption behind the p-values and confidence intervals. The lesson: never report R² without looking at the residuals. To model a curved relationship, switch the Fit Trend model to polynomial/exponential and re-check the residuals. Galton (1886); Anscombe (1973).",
      "x": 40,
      "y": 24,
      "width": 360,
      "height": 190
    }
  ],
